{{distinguish|Ah Toy}} {{Infobox person |name = Lily Ah Toy |image = Lily Ah Toy at table.jpg |image_size = 150 |birth_date = {{birth date|1917|10|24}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE1826b.htm|title=Ah Toy, Lily (1917 - 2001)|publisher=The Australian Women's Register|date=24 January 2006|last=Henningham|first=Nikki|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> |birth_place = [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Northern Territory]], [[Australia]] |birth_name = Wong Wu Len |death_date = {{death date and age|2001|10|15|1917|10|24}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.territorystories.nt.gov.au/handle/10070/218063|title=Lily Ah Toy|publisher=Territory Stories|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> |death_place = [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Northern Territory]], [[Australia]] |children = 5 (5 more adopted) }}
'''Lily Ah Toy''' (born '''Wong Wu Len''') was an Australian pioneer and businesswoman famous in the [[Northern Territory]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Histories of the Chinese in Australasia and the South Pacific|last=Giese|first=Diana|pages=261–273|editor-last=MacGregor|editor-first=Paul|date=1995}}, cited in {{Cite web|url=http://www.chia.chinesemuseum.com.au/biogs/CH01220b.htm|title=Ah Toy, Lily|publisher=[[Chinese Museum, Melbourne|Chinese Museum]]|date=29 March 2006|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>
==Biography==
On 24 October 1917, Ah Toy was born in Darwin. She was of Chinese heritage. She attended Darwin Public School and left when she was 14 to become a housemaid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/ahtoy/|title=Lily Ah Toy|publisher=Australian Biography|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> On 9 November 1936, she married Jimmy Ah Toy, taking his surname.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weekendnotes.com/pine-creek-places-to-go/|title=Pine Creek - Places to Go|publisher=''Weekend Notes''|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> She then set up a general store in Pine Creek. She had five children of her own, and adopted five more. She then moved to [[Adelaide]], before moving back to Pine Creek in 1945. In 1988, she was honoured as one of eight Northern Territorians who had made a significant contribution to the territory. Ah Toy died in Darwin on 15 October 2001.
