{{Infobox company | name = MRS Oil Nigeria PLC | logo = | type = [[Public company|Public]] | industry = [[Oil and gas]] | fate = | predecessor = {{Unbulleted list|Chevron Nigeria Plc|Texaco Nigeria Plc}} | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] --> | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = Lagos | hq_location_country = Nigeria | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = Patrice Albert | products = {{Unbulleted list|[[Motor spirit|Premium Motor Spirit]]|[[Diesel fuel|AGO]]|[[Kerosene|dual purpose kerosene]]|[[Jet fuel|Aviation kerosene]] }} | revenue = 107.088 billion naira<ref name="reuters" /> | revenue_year = 2017 | operating_income = | income_year = | net_income = 1,385,100,000 naira<ref name="reuters" /> | net_income_year = 2017 | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''MRS Oil Nigeria Plc''' is a [[Nigeria]]n oil marketing company with headquarters in Lagos. The firm previously traded under the name of Texaco Nigeria Plc.
MRS Oil has three business units: sale of petroleum at retail outlets or to industries, sale of aviation fuel and blending of lubricants.<ref name="reuters">{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/overview/CHEVRON.LG |title=MRS Oil Nigeria |last=Editorial |first=Reuters |website=U.S. |language=en |access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref>
Previously known as Texaco Nigeria Plc, a firm whose activities in Nigeria dates back to 1969 when it was established to take over the Nigerian trading interest of Texaco Africa Limited.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201307030525.html |title=Nigeria: MRS Oil Nigeria - in Dire Need of Cheaper Funding |last=Egene |first=Goddy |date=2013-07-03 |work=This Day (Lagos) |access-date=2018-07-27}}</ref> In 2009, a consortium of MRS Holdings and Petroci Holdings bought majority stake from Chevron Oil and Gas to form MRS Oil Nigeria PLC.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/05a619de-ca97-11df-a860-00144feab49a |title=Fuel barons: Oligarchs’ party may be over |last=Kantai |first=Parselelo |access-date=2018-07-27 |language=en-GB}}</ref>
