{{Icelandic name|Þórólfur}} {{Infobox person | name = Þórólfur Beck Kristjónsson | image = | birth_date = April 14, 1974 | birth_place = [[Reykjavík]], [[Iceland]] | education = [[Bifröst University]] ([[dropped out]]) | known_for = Co-founding [[CCP Games]] }}
'''Þórólfur Beck Kristjónsson''' (born April 14, 1974) is an [[entrepreneur]], [[game designer]] and [[Video game producer|producer]] best known for co-founding the video game company [[CCP Games]]<ref name="CCPGamesonGiantBomb">[http://www.giantbomb.com/ccp-games/65-5270/ "CCP Games"], [[Giant Bomb]], (Retrieved 29 June 2010)</ref> and creating the board game Hættuspil (Danger Game).<ref name="BifrostThorolfur">[http://www.bifrost.is/islenska/um-haskolann/frettir/nr/130427/ "Frá hugmynd að heimsenda - Þórólfur Beck"], [[Bifröst University]], 12 July 2012, (Retrieved 30 January 2014) {{is icon}}</ref> Hættuspil remains one of Iceland's most popular board games and CCP's video game [[Eve Online|EVE Online]] currently has 500,000 users.<ref name="EveOnlineUsers">[https://www.vg247.com/2013/02/28/eve-online-passes-500000-subscriber-milestone/ "EVE Online passes 500,000 subscribers"], 28 February 2013, (Retrieved 4 October 2017)</ref> EVE also went on to win awards from [[PC Gamer]] magazine and MMORPG.com.<ref name="EveOnlineHome">[http://www.eveonline.com/ "EVE Online Homepage"], CCP Games, (Retrieved 20 November 2015)</ref>
==Early life and education== Beck was born and raised in Reykjavik, Iceland, where he has lived for the majority of his life. While originally wanting to become a pilot, he was always interested in video games. The first video games he played were on the [[Commodore 64]] as well as in arcades; his favorite games and main inspirations were [[Elite (video game)|Elite]], [[Magic: The Gathering]], [[VRML]] and early [[MUD]] titles .<ref name="EurogamerThorolfur">[http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-06-22-meet-thor-beck-the-eve-creator-who-ccp-left-behind "Meet the Eve Online creator who CCP left behind"], [[Eurogamer]], 20 June 2014, (Retrieved 20 November 2015)</ref>
In 2002, Þórólfur enrolled in [[Bifröst University]] in [[Borgarbyggð]] Iceland, where he studied law for two years. In 2004 he was given the opportunity become the agent and producer of an Icelandic music act that went on to compete in a European music competition. He later re-enrolled and continued his studies from 2011 to 2013.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}
==Career== In 1997, along with Reynir Harðarson, Þórólfur founded CCP games <ref name="Eurogamer10YearsOfCCP">[http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=77768&page=2 "10 Years of CCP", Page 2], [[Eurogamer]], 15 June 2007, (Retrieved 20 November 2015)</ref> for the purpose of making [[MMORPG]]s. In order to finance the initial development of ''Eve Online'', CCP developed and published a board game in Iceland called ''Hættuspil'' ("''Danger Game''").<ref name="Eurogamer10YearsOfCCP" /> During his time at CCP, he was majority owner, founder, manager, chairman and sole game designer as well as being the first employee.<ref name="EurogamerThorolfur" /> Þórólfur has since left the company as well as all of the original founders, the last of which left in 2015.
In 2005 Þórólfur became the producer of [[Silvía Night]],<ref name="TimaritThorolfur">Bergþóra Jónsdóttir, [http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=4118097 "Það er í höndum guðs, – hann er sko stílistinn minn"], ''[[Morgunblaðið]]'', 20 May 2006, (Retrieved 30 January 2014) {{is icon}}</ref> an Icelandic singer based on a fictional character who was Iceland's participant in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006]] with the song "Congratulations" after winning the Icelandic national finals. While failing to win the competition, the act continued to be very popular in Iceland and is still remembered as one of countries most entertaining entries.
In 2007 Þórólfur became [[Executive Vice President]] (EVP) of Business Development at [[LazyTown Entertainment]], where he was in charge of tying LazyTown with [[Wal-Mart]] Mexico with the aim of promoting healthy lifestyles and delivering fitness ideas to Mexican children and families.<ref name="WalMartMexicoThorolfur">Samantha Loveday, [http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/lazytown-ties-with-wal-mart-mexico/037352 "LazyTown ties with Wal-Mart Mexico"], Licensing.biz, 13 March 2008, (Retrieved 30 January 2014)</ref> LazyTown Entertainment is an Icelandic children's entertainment company that also brands toys and healthy food items, its main TV show "Lazy Town" (originally "Latibær") was based on a popular Icelandic children play and is one of the fastest growing children's shows in the world.
Beck is currently working on a [[Massively multiplayer online game|MMO]] project under the company name "NARC".<ref name="EurogamerThorolfur" />
